y0RnpIpa7DScMNA\" alt=\"Glitch arena screenshot\"></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Design &amp; Visual Art</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I don\'t do client or even professional design work any more, but here\'s some of my art, graphic art and other design</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://www.behance.net/alidark3000\">AliDark3000 on Behance</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-08-21 08:37:35', '2022-08-21 08:37:35', '', 2, 'http://alidarkssg/?p=69', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(70, 1, '2022-08-21 10:17:21', '2022-08-21 10:17:21', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I like it dirty. Not sexually, or at least, that\'s not what we\'re writing about here. Here, we\'re talking about art. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the last 20 years especially, the we\'ve seen everything we used to do physically shift to digital. It\'s been mostly great - huge efficiencies have meant we can do more of other things. But, we\'ve been absolutely infatuated with it, culturally. For those who weren\'t brain-deep in the internet, the digital world was the modern one - the future - and the one to be aspired to. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But digital didn\'t stop there  - it took over everything. A major downside is that everything in the last 20 years has been so damn clean. This is supposed to be a good thing, of course. Digital artifacts have much higher fidelity in most cases. They can be reproduced perfectly. When you get to the real high end of any medium this proposition falls apart fairly quickly, but for even discerning consumers, digital is better. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><br>Allow Mistakes</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wes Anderson films are dirty. The fingerprints of the filmmaker are all over them. There are subtle and human imperfections everywhere. Camera shots are always straight on to the background, but the lenses are wide, distorting the lines. All this is deliberate. However in the directors commentary on the Darjeeling Limited, Wes takes a phone call. And leaves it in. Dirty bugger. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been longing to get back to </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been wondering what it is I like about analog - and specifically, dirty analog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'I like it Dirty', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-08-21 10:17:21', '2022-08-21 10:17:21', '', 55, 'http://alidarkssg/?p=70', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(71, 1, '2022-08-21 12:03:37', '2022-08-21 12:03:37', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the last 20 years especially, the we\'ve seen everything we used to do physically shift to digital. It\'s been mostly great - huge efficiencies have meant we can do more of other things. But, we\'ve been absolutely infatuated with it, culturally. For those who weren\'t brain-deep in the internet, the digital world was the modern one - the future - and the one to be aspired to. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But digital didn\'t stop there  - it took over everything. A major downside is that everything in the last 20 years has been so damn clean. This is supposed to be a good thing, of course. Digital artifacts have much higher fidelity in most cases. They can be reproduced perfectly. When you get to the real high end of any medium this proposition falls apart fairly quickly, but for even discerning consumers, digital is better. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirtiness can be deliberate, like me setting my camera to Iso 12800. But it shouldn\'t, ideally, be digital post-processing. Unless digital post-processing is the look you\'re going for. There\'s a really fine lines crisscrossing this issue from all angles. I\'ll try to identify them by examples. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Allow Mistakes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wes Anderson films are dirty. The fingerprints of the filmmaker are all over them. There are subtle and human imperfections everywhere. Camera shots are always straight on to the background, but the lenses are wide, distorting the lines. All this is deliberate. However in the directors commentary on the Darjeeling Limited, Wes takes a phone call. And leaves it in. Dirty bugger. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been longing to get back to </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been wondering what it is I like about analog - and specifically, dirty analog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'A Theory of Dirty', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-08-21 12:03:37', '2022-08-21 12:03:37', '', 55, 'http://alidarkssg/?p=71', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(72, 1, '2022-08-21 12:05:46', '2022-08-21 12:05:46', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the last 20 years especially, the we\'ve seen everything we used to do physically shift to digital. It\'s been mostly great - huge efficiencies have meant we can do more of other things. But, we\'ve been absolutely infatuated with it, culturally. For those who weren\'t brain-deep in the internet, the digital world was the modern one - the future - and the one to be aspired to. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But digital didn\'t stop there  - it took over everything. A major downside is that everything in the last 20 years has been so damn clean. This is supposed to be a good thing, of course. Digital artifacts have much higher fidelity in most cases. They can be reproduced perfectly. When you get to the real high end of any medium this proposition falls apart fairly quickly, but for even discerning consumers, digital is better. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirtiness can be deliberate, like me setting my camera to Iso 12800. But it shouldn\'t, ideally, be digital post-processing. Unless digital post-processing is the look you\'re going for. There\'s a really fine lines crisscrossing this issue from all angles. I\'ll try to identify them by examples. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Allow Mistakes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wes Anderson films are dirty. The fingerprints of the filmmaker are all over them. There are subtle and human imperfections everywhere. Camera shots are always straight on to the background, but the lenses are wide, distorting the lines. All this is deliberate. However in the directors commentary on the Darjeeling Limited, Wes takes a phone call. And leaves it in. Dirty bugger. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wrong notes, bumps and static, these things let us feel the humanness of art. Electronic musicians not quantizing their melodies to the beat. Or not even quantizing their beat to the time. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been longing to get back to </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been wondering what it is I like about analog - and specifically, dirty analog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'A Theory of Dirty', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-08-21 12:05:46', '2022-08-21 12:05:46', '', 55, 'http://alidarkssg/?p=72', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(73, 1, '2022-08-21 12:08:06', '2022-08-21 12:08:06', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the last 20 years especially, the we\'ve seen everything we used to do physically shift to digital. It\'s been mostly great - huge efficiencies have meant we can do more of other things. But, we\'ve been absolutely infatuated with it, culturally. For those who weren\'t brain-deep in the internet, the digital world was the modern one - the future - and the one to be aspired to. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But digital didn\'t stop there  - it took over everything. A major downside is that everything in the last 20 years has been so damn clean. This is supposed to be a good thing, of course. Digital artifacts have much higher fidelity in most cases. They can be reproduced perfectly. When you get to the real high end of any medium this proposition falls apart fairly quickly, but for even discerning consumers, digital is better. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirtiness can be deliberate, like me setting my camera to Iso 12800. But it shouldn\'t, ideally, be digital post-processing. Unless digital post-processing is the look you\'re going for. There\'s a really fine lines crisscrossing this issue from all angles. I\'ll try to identify them by examples. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best examples of dirty are analog. I have a book of posters from punk bands. This counts highly. Zines - when made with a photocopier.. not so much when they\'re made to look like they\'re made with a photocopier. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Integrity</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty shouldn\'t be a look, it should be come from the method. The process should be journey. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Allow Mistakes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wes Anderson films are dirty. The fingerprints of the filmmaker are all over them. There are subtle and human imperfections everywhere. Camera shots are always straight on to the background, but the lenses are wide, distorting the lines. All this is deliberate. However in the directors commentary on the Darjeeling Limited, Wes takes a phone call. And leaves it in. Dirty bugger. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wrong notes, bumps and static, these things let us feel the humanness of art. Electronic musicians not quantizing their melodies to the beat. Or not even quantizing their beat to the time. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been longing to get back to </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been wondering what it is I like about analog - and specifically, dirty analog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'A Theory of Dirty', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-08-21 12:08:06', '2022-08-21 12:08:06', '', 55, 'http://alidarkssg/?p=73', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(74, 1, '2022-08-21 12:10:07', '2022-08-21 12:10:07', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the last 20 years especially, the we\'ve seen everything we used to do physically shift to digital. It\'s been mostly great - huge efficiencies have meant we can do more of other things. But, we\'ve been absolutely infatuated with it, culturally. For those who weren\'t brain-deep in the internet, the digital world was the modern one - the future - and the one to be aspired to. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But digital didn\'t stop there  - it took over everything. A major downside is that everything in the last 20 years has been so damn clean. This is supposed to be a good thing, of course. Digital artifacts have much higher fidelity in most cases. They can be reproduced perfectly. When you get to the real high end of any medium this proposition falls apart fairly quickly, but for even discerning consumers, digital is better. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirtiness can be deliberate, like me setting my camera to Iso 12800. But it shouldn\'t, ideally, be digital post-processing. Unless digital post-processing is the look you\'re going for. There\'s a really fine lines crisscrossing this issue from all angles. I\'ll try to identify them by examples. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best examples of dirty are analog. I have a book of posters from punk bands. This counts highly. Zines - when made with a photocopier.. not so much when they\'re made to look like they\'re made with a photocopier. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Integrity</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty shouldn\'t be a look, it should be come from the method. The process should be a dirty. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can buy a photocopier photoshop template that will run your image through some processes to affect a photocopied look. Or, you can get a photocopier. One of those is easier and cheaper than the other. But one should not be an option. In design, maybe... whatever, I mean you\'ve sold your creativity to business so what does it matter anyway? But in Art? Noooo. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Allow Mistakes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wes Anderson films are dirty. The fingerprints of the filmmaker are all over them. There are subtle and human imperfections everywhere. Camera shots are always straight on to the background, but the lenses are wide, distorting the lines. All this is deliberate. However in the directors commentary on the Darjeeling Limited, Wes takes a phone call. And leaves it in. Dirty bugger. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wrong notes, bumps and static, these things let us feel the humanness of art. Electronic musicians not quantizing their melodies to the beat. Or not even quantizing their beat to the time. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been longing to get back to </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been wondering what it is I like about analog - and specifically, dirty analog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'A Theory of Dirty', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-08-21 12:10:07', '2022-08-21 12:10:07', '', 55, 'http://alidarkssg/?p=74', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(75, 1, '2022-08-21 12:32:28', '2022-08-21 12:32:28', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the last 20 years especially, the we\'ve seen everything we used to do physically shift to digital. It\'s been mostly great - huge efficiencies have meant we can do more of other things. But, we\'ve been absolutely infatuated with it, culturally. For those who weren\'t brain-deep in the internet, the digital world was the modern one - the future - and the one to be aspired to. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But digital didn\'t stop there  - it took over everything. A major downside is that everything in the last 20 years has been so damn clean. This is supposed to be a good thing, of course. Digital artifacts have much higher fidelity in most cases. They can be reproduced perfectly. When you get to the real high end of any medium this proposition falls apart fairly quickly, but for even discerning consumers, digital is better. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirtiness can be deliberate, like me setting my camera to Iso 12800. But it shouldn\'t, ideally, be digital post-processing. Unless digital post-processing is the look you\'re going for. There\'s a really fine lines crisscrossing this issue from all angles. I\'ll try to identify them by examples. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My brain, at least, likes analog, because it\'s more interesting to listen to - less repetitive, even when it is repetitive. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best examples of dirty are analog. I have a book of posters from punk bands. This counts highly. Zines - when made with a photocopier.. not so much when they\'re made to look like they\'re made with a photocopier. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Integrity</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty shouldn\'t be a look, it should be come from the method. The process should be a dirty. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can buy a photocopier photoshop template that will run your image through some processes to affect a photocopied look. Or, you can get a photocopier. One of those is easier and cheaper than the other. But one should not be an option. In design, maybe... whatever, I mean you\'ve sold your creativity to business so what does it matter anyway? But in Art? Noooo. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Allow Mistakes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wes Anderson films are dirty. The fingerprints of the filmmaker are all over them. There are subtle and human imperfections everywhere. Camera shots are always straight on to the background, but the lenses are wide, distorting the lines. All this is deliberate. However in the directors commentary on the Darjeeling Limited, Wes takes a phone call. And leaves it in. Dirty bugger. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wrong notes, bumps and static, these things let us feel the humanness of art. Electronic musicians not quantizing their melodies to the beat. Or not even quantizing their beat to the time. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been longing to get back to </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been wondering what it is I like about analog - and specifically, dirty analog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Digital as the transfer medium, not the medium.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Electronic Music</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The digital medium has opened up huge opportunities in all creative fields. Take music. In the 90s you needed a room full of heavy, power-hungry and prohibitively expensive equipment to make professional music. But in 2005, I had a track released that I had made exclusively on a computer. I would not be able to have done this in the 90s without a next-level level of commitment. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So I can\'t say that we shouldn\'t make things with computers. And I don\'t want to! But maybe it\'s fun to limit the involvement of the computer sometimes, and producing sounds in the real world, and use the computer to put it together. Great dirtiness is found this way. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can get dirty in sound by modulating digital sounds with analog ones. For example, changing the volume of a track by side-chaining in another loop. In my track <a href=\"https://music.youtube.com/watch?v=chBRrgOSUkE&amp;feature=share\">Gravity in Space</a>, I ran a noise gate over some of the sounds and modulated like that. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'A Theory of Dirty', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-08-21 12:32:28', '2022-08-21 12:32:28', '', 55, 'http://alidarkssg/?p=75', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(76, 1, '2022-08-21 12:44:00', '2022-08-21 12:44:00', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the last 20 years especially, the we\'ve seen everything we used to do physically shift to digital. It\'s been mostly great - huge efficiencies have meant we can do more of other things. But, we\'ve been absolutely infatuated with it, culturally. For those who weren\'t brain-deep in the internet, the digital world was the modern one - the future - and the one to be aspired to. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But digital didn\'t stop there  - it took over everything. A major downside is that everything in the last 20 years has been so damn clean. This is supposed to be a good thing, of course. Digital artifacts have much higher fidelity in most cases. They can be reproduced perfectly. When you get to the real high end of any medium this proposition falls apart fairly quickly, but for even discerning consumers, digital is better. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirtiness can be deliberate, like me setting my camera to Iso 12800. But it shouldn\'t, ideally, be digital post-processing. Unless digital post-processing is the look you\'re going for. There\'s a really fine lines crisscrossing this issue from all angles. I\'ll try to identify them by examples. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My brain, at least, likes analog, because it\'s more interesting to listen to - less repetitive, even when it is repetitive. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best examples of dirty are analog. I have a book of posters from punk bands. This counts highly. Zines - when made with a photocopier.. not so much when they\'re made to look like they\'re made with a photocopier. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Integrity</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty shouldn\'t be a look, it should be come from the method. The process should be a dirty. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can buy a photocopier photoshop template that will run your image through some processes to affect a photocopied look. Or, you can get a photocopier. One of those is easier and cheaper than the other. But one should not be an option. In design, maybe... whatever, I mean you\'ve sold your creativity to business so what does it matter anyway? But in Art? Noooo. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Allow Mistakes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wes Anderson films are dirty. The fingerprints of the filmmaker are all over them. There are subtle and human imperfections everywhere. Camera shots are always straight on to the background, but the lenses are wide, distorting the lines. All this is deliberate. However in the directors commentary on the Darjeeling Limited, Wes takes a phone call. And leaves it in. Dirty bugger. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wrong notes, bumps and static, these things let us feel the humanness of art. Electronic musicians not quantizing their melodies to the beat. Or not even quantizing their beat to the time. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been longing to get back to </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been wondering what it is I like about analog - and specifically, dirty analog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Digital as the transfer medium, not the medium.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Electronic Music</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sonic Youth is dirty. The dirtiest, maybe, if you don\'t count the 5,6,7,8s who sing with no regard for frequency, in their second language. But it\'s not just loosey goosey analog music that can be dirty. Electronic music is evolving this way too. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The digital medium has opened up huge opportunities in all creative fields. Take music. In the 90s you needed a room full of heavy, power-hungry and prohibitively expensive equipment to make professional music. But in 2005, I had a track released that I had made exclusively on a computer. I would not be able to have done this in the 90s without a next-level level of commitment. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So I can\'t say that we shouldn\'t make things with computers. And I don\'t want to! But maybe it\'s fun to limit the involvement of the computer sometimes, and producing sounds in the real world, and use the computer to put it together. Great dirtiness is found this way. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can get dirty in sound by modulating digital sounds with analog ones. For example, changing the volume of a track by side-chaining in another loop. In my track <a href=\"https://music.youtube.com/watch?v=chBRrgOSUkE&amp;feature=share\">Gravity in Space</a>, I ran a noise gate over some of the sounds and modulated like that. Once I had setup how it worked, it was out of my control, and that\'s what I wanted. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Dirty web design</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty means different things when applied to different medium. If you take the laziness of Sonic Youth vocals and translate that to the web, what have you got? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty on the web could mean raw, unrefined websites. It could mean graphically dirty elements, but I don\'t like this because it would need to be done carefully to ensure the content is accessible. The web is volatile. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'A Theory of Dirty', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-08-21 12:44:00', '2022-08-21 12:44:00', '', 55, 'http://alidarkssg/?p=76', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(77, 1, '2022-08-21 12:47:22', '2022-08-21 12:47:22', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the last 20 years especially, the we\'ve seen everything we used to do physically shift to digital. It\'s been mostly great - huge efficiencies have meant we can do more of other things. But, we\'ve been absolutely infatuated with it, culturally. For those who weren\'t brain-deep in the internet, the digital world was the modern one - the future - and the one to be aspired to. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But digital didn\'t stop there  - it took over everything. A major downside is that everything in the last 20 years has been so damn clean. This is supposed to be a good thing, of course. Digital artifacts have much higher fidelity in most cases. They can be reproduced perfectly. When you get to the real high end of any medium this proposition falls apart fairly quickly, but for even discerning consumers, digital is better. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirtiness can be deliberate, like me setting my camera to Iso 12800. But it shouldn\'t, ideally, be digital post-processing. Unless digital post-processing is the look you\'re going for. There\'s a really fine lines crisscrossing this issue from all angles. I\'ll try to identify them by examples. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My brain, at least, likes analog, because it\'s more interesting to listen to - less repetitive, even when it is repetitive. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best examples of dirty are analog. I have a book of posters from punk bands. This counts highly. Zines - when made with a photocopier.. not so much when they\'re made to look like they\'re made with a photocopier. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Integrity</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty shouldn\'t be a style, it should be come from the method. The process should be a dirty. Even if the results are the same (they won\'t be), a dirty process is more fun. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can buy a photocopier photoshop template that will run your image through some processes to affect a photocopied look. Or, you can get a photocopier. One of those is easier and cheaper than the other. But one should not be an option. In design, maybe... whatever, I mean you\'ve sold your creativity to business so what does it matter anyway? But in Art? Noooo. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Allow Mistakes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wes Anderson films are dirty. The fingerprints of the filmmaker are all over them. There are subtle and human imperfections everywhere. Camera shots are always straight on to the background, but the lenses are wide, distorting the lines. All this is deliberate. However in the directors commentary on the Darjeeling Limited, Wes takes a phone call. And leaves it in. Dirty bugger. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wrong notes, bumps and static, these things let us feel the humanness of art. Electronic musicians not quantizing their melodies to the beat. Or not even quantizing their beat to the time. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been longing to get back to </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been wondering what it is I like about analog - and specifically, dirty analog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Digital as the transfer medium, not the medium.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Electronic Music</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sonic Youth is dirty. The dirtiest, maybe, if you don\'t count the 5,6,7,8s who sing with no regard for frequency, in their second language. But it\'s not just loosey goosey analog music that can be dirty. Electronic music is evolving this way too. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The digital medium has opened up huge opportunities in all creative fields. Take music. In the 90s you needed a room full of heavy, power-hungry and prohibitively expensive equipment to make professional music. But in 2005, I had a track released that I had made exclusively on a computer. I would not be able to have done this in the 90s without a next-level level of commitment. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So I can\'t say that we shouldn\'t make things with computers. And I don\'t want to! But maybe it\'s fun to limit the involvement of the computer sometimes, and producing sounds in the real world, and use the computer to put it together. Great dirtiness is found this way - in play. Achieving dirtiness deliberately takes the fun out of it. It still might be fun to listen to, but I\'d bet not <em>as </em>fun. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can get dirty in sound by modulating digital sounds with analog ones. For example, changing the volume of a track by side-chaining in another loop. In my track <a href=\"https://music.youtube.com/watch?v=chBRrgOSUkE&amp;feature=share\">Gravity in Space</a>, I ran a noise gate over some of the sounds and modulated like that. Once I had setup how it worked, it was out of my control, and that\'s what I wanted. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Dirty web design</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty means different things when applied to different medium. If you take the laziness of Sonic Youth vocals and translate that to the web, what have you got? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty on the web could mean raw, unrefined websites. It could mean graphically dirty elements, but I don\'t like this because it would need to be done carefully to ensure the content is accessible. The web is volatile. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'A Theory of Dirty', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-08-21 12:47:22', '2022-08-21 12:47:22', '', 55, 'http://alidarkssg/?p=77', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(78, 1, '2022-08-21 12:50:20', '2022-08-21 12:50:20', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The evolution of creativity in a digital age. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the last 20 years especially, the we\'ve seen everything we used to do physically shift to digital. It\'s been mostly great - huge efficiencies have meant we can do more of other things. But, we\'ve been absolutely infatuated with it, culturally. For those who weren\'t brain-deep in the internet, the digital world was the modern one - the future - and the one to be aspired to. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But digital didn\'t stop there  - it took over everything. A major downside is that everything in the last 20 years has been so damn clean. This is supposed to be a good thing, of course. Digital artifacts have much higher fidelity in most cases. They can be reproduced perfectly. When you get to the real high end of any medium this proposition falls apart fairly quickly, but for even discerning consumers, digital is better. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirtiness can be deliberate, like me setting my camera to Iso 12800. But it shouldn\'t, ideally, be digital post-processing. Unless digital post-processing is the look you\'re going for. There\'s a really fine lines crisscrossing this issue from all angles. I\'ll try to identify them by examples. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My brain, at least, likes analog, because it\'s more interesting to listen to - less repetitive, even when it is repetitive. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best examples of dirty are analog. I have a book of posters from punk bands. This counts highly. Zines - when made with a photocopier.. not so much when they\'re made to look like they\'re made with a photocopier. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Integrity</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty shouldn\'t be a style, it should be come from the method. The process should be a dirty. Even if the results are the same (they won\'t be), a dirty process is more fun. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can buy a photocopier photoshop template that will run your image through some processes to affect a photocopied look. Or, you can get a photocopier. One of those is easier and cheaper than the other. But one should not be an option. In design, maybe... whatever, I mean you\'ve sold your creativity to business so what does it matter anyway? But in Art? Noooo. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Allow Mistakes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wes Anderson films are dirty. The fingerprints of the filmmaker are all over them. There are subtle and human imperfections everywhere. Camera shots are always straight on to the background, but the lenses are wide, distorting the lines. All this is deliberate. However in the directors commentary on the Darjeeling Limited, Wes takes a phone call. And leaves it in. Dirty bugger. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wrong notes, bumps and static, these things let us feel the humanness of art. Electronic musicians not quantizing their melodies to the beat. Or not even quantizing their beat to the time. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Dirtiness is hard</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been longing to get back to a more natural state in my creativity. But with the conveniences of digital, it feels weird to be <em>going out of my way</em> to make something more natural. The more I do this though, the more I learn that it is <em>worth it</em>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ve been wondering what it is I like about analog - and specifically, dirty analog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Digital as the transfer medium, not the medium.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Electronic Music</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sonic Youth is dirty. The dirtiest, maybe, if you don\'t count the 5,6,7,8s who sing with no regard for frequency, in their second language. But it\'s not just loosey goosey analog music that can be dirty. Electronic music is evolving this way too. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The digital medium has opened up huge opportunities in all creative fields. Take music. In the 90s you needed a room full of heavy, power-hungry and prohibitively expensive equipment to make professional music. But in 2005, I had a track released that I had made exclusively on a computer. I would not be able to have done this in the 90s without a next-level level of commitment. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So I can\'t say that we shouldn\'t make things with computers. And I don\'t want to! But maybe it\'s fun to limit the involvement of the computer sometimes, and producing sounds in the real world, and use the computer to put it together. Great dirtiness is found this way - in play. Achieving dirtiness deliberately takes the fun out of it. It still might be fun to listen to, but I\'d bet not <em>as </em>fun. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can get dirty in sound by modulating digital sounds with analog ones. For example, changing the volume of a track by side-chaining in another loop. In my track <a href=\"https://music.youtube.com/watch?v=chBRrgOSUkE&amp;feature=share\">Gravity in Space</a>, I ran a noise gate over some of the sounds and modulated like that. Once I had setup how it worked, it was out of my control, and that\'s what I wanted. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Dirty web design</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty means different things when applied to different medium. If you take the laziness of Sonic Youth vocals and translate that to the web, what have you got? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dirty on the web could mean raw, unrefined websites. It could mean graphically dirty elements, but I don\'t like this because it would need to be done carefully to ensure the content is accessible. The web is volatile. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'A Theory of Dirty', 'The evolution of creativity in a digital age. ', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-08-21 12:50:20', '2022-08-21 12:50:20', '', 55, 'http://alidarkssg/?p=78', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
